{"award_age":46.0,"bio_image":"full\/302cdb8430d7c2beb0f70cf8946f2f419a18b07f.jpg","category":"Physiology or Medicine","country":"United Kingdom","date_of_birth":"1917-11-22T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"2012-05-30T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/c\/c7\/Andrew_Fielding_Huxley_nobel.jpg\/192px-Andrew_Fielding_Huxley_nobel.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Andrew_Huxley","mini_bio":"<p><b>Sir Andrew Fielding Huxley<\/b>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Order_of_Merit_(Commonwealth)\" title=\"Order of Merit (Commonwealth)\" class=\"mw-redirect\">OM<\/a>, <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/President_of_the_Royal_Society\" title=\"President of the Royal Society\" class=\"mw-redirect\">PRS<\/a> (22 November 1917\u00a0\u2013 30 May 2012) was a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize<\/a>-winning English <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Physiology\" title=\"Physiology\">physiologist<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Biophysics\" title=\"Biophysics\">biophysicist<\/a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-huxley1996_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Andrew_Huxley#cite_note-huxley1996-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Andrew_Huxley#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> He was born into the prominent <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Huxley_family\" title=\"Huxley family\">Huxley family<\/a>. After graduating from <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Westminster_School\" title=\"Westminster School\">Westminster School<\/a> in Central London, from where he won a scholarship to <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Trinity_College,_Cambridge\" title=\"Trinity College, Cambridge\">Trinity College, Cambridge<\/a>, he joined <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Alan_Lloyd_Hodgkin\" title=\"Alan Lloyd Hodgkin\">Alan Lloyd Hodgkin<\/a> to study nerve impulses. Their eventual discovery of the basis propagation of nerve impulses (called action potential) earned them the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physiology_or_Medicine\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine\">Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine<\/a> in 1963. They made their discovery from the giant <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Axon\" title=\"Axon\">axon<\/a> of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Loligo_pealei\" title=\"Loligo pealei\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Atlantic squid<\/a>. Soon after the outbreak of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Second_World_War\" title=\"Second World War\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Second World War<\/a>, Huxley was recruited by the British Anti-Aircraft Command and later transferred to the Admiralty. After the war he resumed research at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Cambridge_University\" title=\"Cambridge University\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Cambridge University<\/a>, where he developed <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Interference_microscopy\" title=\"Interference microscopy\">interference microscopy<\/a> that would be suitable for studying muscle fibres. In 1952 he was joined by a German physiologist <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Rolf_Niedergerke\" title=\"Rolf Niedergerke\">Rolf Niedergerke<\/a>. Together they discovered in 1954 the mechanism of muscle contraction, popularly called the \"<a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Sliding_filament_theory\" title=\"Sliding filament theory\" class=\"mw-redirect\">sliding filament theory<\/a>\", which is the foundation of modern understanding of muscle mechanics. In 1960 he became head of the Department of Physiology at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_College_London\" title=\"University College London\">University College London<\/a>. He was elected a Fellow of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Royal_Society\" title=\"Royal Society\">Royal Society<\/a> in 1955, and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/President_of_the_Royal_Society\" title=\"President of the Royal Society\" class=\"mw-redirect\">President<\/a> in 1980. The Royal Society awarded him the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Copley_Medal\" title=\"Copley Medal\">Copley Medal<\/a> in 1973 for his collective contribution to nerve impulse and muscle contraction. He was conferred <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Knight_Bachelor\" title=\"Knight Bachelor\">Knight Bachelor<\/a> by <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Queen_Elizabeth_II\" title=\"Queen Elizabeth II\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Queen Elizabeth II<\/a> in 1974, and was appointed to the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Order_of_Merit\" title=\"Order of Merit\">Order of Merit<\/a> in 1983. He was a fellow of Trinity College, Cambridge, until his death.<\/p>","name":"Andrew Huxley","place_of_birth":"Hampstead , London, England, UK","place_of_death":"Grantchester, Cambridgeshire, England , UK","text":"Andrew Huxley , Physiology or Medicine, 1963","year":1963.0}